\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You are }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  in 1921?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You were born in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 1897.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And the place was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Lowfell, Co. Durham. It's near Newcastle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I just lived ... I was born ... Father built a row of houses, they weren't big, and my brother was bor
n ... it was called The Weathercock, that's a funny name. My brother was born there and I was born there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How many years did you live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I think I lived about one year, because I can't remember going along to Beaconsfield Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Where did you live then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Afterwards? Oh, we went to Beaconsfield Road. We moved to a bigger house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But it was still in Lowfell, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How long did you live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 'Till I was ... in 1912 ... no, Father retired in 1912 and we 
lived there 'till ... now this is clear in my mind, we lived there 'till May, 1914. The War broke out in August, '14.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Where did you go then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We never went anywhere else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, I got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  from there.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But you said you left Beaconsfield Road in May 1914?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, eh ... you're muddling me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I see, so you moved over the road in Beaconsfield Road to No. 30?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, to No. 30.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you lived there until you got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 'Till I got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  in 1921.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember why your family moved in the first place from The Weathercock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, we got more prosperous, we moved up, I suppose, in the world.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And so you bought a bigger house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And why did you move over the road from ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Because it was a much nicer house. My mother wanted that house when they were first }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  and Father said 'well, I can't afford you those houses', but he did eventually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You had one brother you told me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And he was 2 years older than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 2 1/2 years older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 He was born in 1895?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 That's funny. I know he was a lot older than Mother. Put that off for a minute.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 So, we decided your father was 43 when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 That must be by that calculation. Roughly, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 He was born and bred in Lowfell, Durham, and never went out of it, except for his honeymoon, and he went away for 3 days up to Bamburgh an
d just stayed 2.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What was his occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 He was a provision dealer, a tea dealer. It's been in the family, I think, 200 years, the business. My brother didn't want it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did he have any other job before he took over the family business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, no. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Not afterwards either?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, no. He retired in 1912.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 He never had any sort of part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, no, never. He had plenty of part time hobbies, but part time jobs were just a piece of
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you ever remember him being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Never! Never. We were a prosperous family. When people were down and out they were the ones that helped, and they were very good helpers. They're remembered to this day; people are dying out now, but ... they were really good people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember how old your mother was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, she was 8 years younger than Father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 So she would have been 35?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes. Because she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
, I think when she was 28 and she was 5 years }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 , I think, before Gordon was born. That's just her telling, me, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 So she would be 33 to 35?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 She came from Scotland, from Duns in Berwickshire, and they came because they opened a gas works, you know, down in the Teams 
and the first gas works was opened down there and her uncle was the first manager of the gas works and, of course, he brought his sister, my grandma, and her husband there, and they had 2 or 3 sons and they all got work there. And the gas works was ... it
 was \{BLANK\} on the Tyne, and that was when gas first came in, and then everybody got gas into their houses, which was marvelous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she have any jobs before she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, she was a sewing maid to a rich lady, a Miss Craig.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she work after she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never. She worked hard in the house, but she didn't do any regular work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Not part time, or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, no, we had servants of our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Now, I'd like to ask you about life at home when you were a child, up to when you left school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, I wasn't much of a child. I was 17.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, up to when you left school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember how many rooms there were in the house at Beaconsfield Road? Let's say the first one you lived in, No. 31, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, there was a big sitting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3015624\charrsid2560445  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 room and a big kitchen. It was a lovely kitchen which was used as a dining}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3015624\charrsid2560445  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
room, and there was a scullery, but there was no bathroom and no hot and cold water. And there were 3 bedrooms and 2 attics.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did anyone else besides your parents and your brother live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, just ourselves. We never had any lodgers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your mother pay anyone to help her in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes, and what funny people we got.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did they live in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. There was the washerwoman, the woman who came to clean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she have just one person, or several? I mean at the same time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Sometimes we'd have 2.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What would be their duties? What would they have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, they'd wash a
nd they'd clean and they'd scrub and they cleaned windows and all sorts of things. They did the chores. We did them more thoroughly than we do them today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she look after the children at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes. And then we had a girl, a Mary Ellen Powe
ll, she was never called Mary or Ellen, but always Mary Ellen, and she used to come along daily and take us out, or if Mother and Father were going, she used to stay and look after us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How did you get on with Mary Ellen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, Mary Ellen. Long, long after I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  Mary Ellen used to come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And when you were a child you liked her, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, we loved Mary Ellen. She was a big, warm, nice girl. We loved Mary Ellen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about the other people who came in to help your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, they were more elderly women.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember any one of them in particular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I remember them all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And how did you get on with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, well, they were just one of us. Father would never keep anybody sitting in a little back 
kitchen, they even sat down with us and had the same meals as we had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What did she call you and your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, she always called ... Mary Ellen called Mother Mrs. Gardiner and just called me Marggie 'till she died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And what about the other people who came in and helped?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Mrs. Gibson came to wash, she was a proper comedienne. And then there was Margaret used to come and wash.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she call your mother Mrs. Gardiner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, Mrs. Gardiner, and ... never 'madam', or anything like that, not up there, we didn't ... not like that at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Was the washing done at home or was it sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 It was done at home! I should say so, my Goodness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your mother or father mend or make your family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, no, Mother 
was no sewer, but I had aunts, her sisters, who were splendid knitters and sewers, knit us socks and we always had everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Who mended the family's clothes, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, Mother was no sewer, she was a lovely cook, but I don't think she liked sewing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she get anybody to do it for her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes, we had a dressmaker. But I think ... she had a sister, and Aunt Lizzie who was a wonderful sewer and I think if anything was done she made \{BLANK\} because she was very clever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have new, or secondhand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never secondhand! We gave them to people. You forget, we were affluent!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about shoes? Did you buy shoes, or were they ever made by anybody in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 There was a very good shoe shop in Newcastle, Oliver, and ... we thought they were expensive then, and we used to go there. Oliver's.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your father ever help your mother with any of the jobs in the house? Like cleaning, or cooking, or washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 He used to put the kettle on sometimes, but he use
d to put it with the spout facing up the chimney, which irritated her. No, he never did anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did he ever make the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Not if he could help it. No, he liked his horses and his dog and his garden, but he was no housemaid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about decorating and repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, we always had decorators in. We never bothered ... and of course, Father was one of these very reliable, steady men, that you had no worry with him squandering money or coming in drunk or doing anything like that, but a ver
y peaceful ... it was what you'd call the long garden party, from 1900 'till the War broke out and things got all mixed up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When you were a child did you have any tasks that you had to carry out regularly at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 To help your mother? What were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I had to clean the scullery window on a Saturday morning. I didn't have to, but she made me do it, to earn the penny I got, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Was that the only thing that you had to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And I cleaned the stair rods. That was the end. That was the shores.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you continue doing that after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I left school and just stayed at home, more for company for Mother, because I didn't do much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you go on cleaning the scullery window and the stair rods after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 The scullery window was gone, then, we had the kitchen. No, I didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Did your brother help you at all with things you found difficult when you were a child? Would he help you to dress, or eat, or anything like that? Do you remember him helping you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, but he was ... he's still very peculiar. People say I'm peculiar, but I don't know. I once had to go to a party and Mother said to Gordon, 'Take Marggie to the party'. He says No, I'll watch out of the front window'. It was just along the
 road. And when I went through the door he said to Mother 'I'll bet she's the nicest little girl there, you know'. But he couldn't show much emotion. Never could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did he help you in any practical way when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, but he didn't figh
t or ... No, he's a very agreeable boy. He's a mischievous mortal, but very, very agreeable. Very agreeable, we never had a wrong word, and I can say that and the world could hear it. Never had a wrong word. Never fought over anything. He'd give you the b
est bite of the apple every time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time, in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
I think Mother was very lenient. You could ... you didn't go to bed late, but you could stay up later if there was any 'do' on. We used to go 
to Chapel, you know, and if there was a bazaar or or any do, well, you could stay up late, come home late with your parents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What time would you normally go to bed, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, about ... I should think about 8, and as we got older, of course, we stayed up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you put yourself to bed or did your mother put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Mother would come up, but if she was busy she'd say 'oh, get away up'. And I had a little Yorkshire terrier at the time and it used to go to bed with me, and as 
soon as I said my prayers it went to bed on a couch. And then as soon as I stopped saying me prayers at night ... I said them on Mother's knee ... then it thought the day was over, and it was a standing joke. Mother used to say at 12 o'clock, at dinnertim
e, 'say your prayers' and the dog used to go to bed (laughter). We had funny dogs and cats. Mother never objected, you could keep what you liked, a dog or a cat or a dove or mice or whatever you liked, there was no restrictions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 At what age to you remember putting yourself to bed for the first time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, you'd run upstairs to bed and then Mother would come up, maybe in about half an hour, see if you were tucked in and everything was O.K.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you share the bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, we always had ... you see, I only had one brother and I had no sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And he had a separate room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And your parents, did they share a bedroom or did they have separate rooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, we had 3 bedrooms. And up 'till '14 it was a peaceable life. Not a sign of anything in the sky as far as we were concerned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You said earlier that you didn't have a bathroom. What room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, we had a lovely ... this big kitchen, then we had this scullery. Well, we boiled the pot that we used 
to boil the clothes in and we bathed there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How often did you have a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, once a week on a Friday night, for sure, but if you were going anywhere special through the week, which was quite frequently, you had another bath. We had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When did you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, we had a clean nightdress and all of this once a week, but if we were going anywhere special - say we were going to town with Mother or your friends, then you had all clean clothes on, which we had quite a lot of clean clothes all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, when we moved over the road we had them in the dining}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3015624\charrsid2560445  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But in this first house in Beaconsfield Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We had this lovely kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You had them in the kitchen. Were there any other occasions when you had them in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I don't think so. What a funny question.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, maybe, say on a Sunday or on Christmas day you might eat somewhere else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, it was such a lovely kitchen, it was nicer than this. Well, after we went to No. 30 we had all our meals in the dining}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3015624\charrsid2560445  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 room; breakfast, dinner, tea and supper, anything, because it was a smaller kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 In the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What sort of equipment was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, it was a range, a black range and the oven was heated by the fire and the boiler in the bathroom - No. 30 had a bathroom - then it was heated at the back of the kitchen fire. We always had hot water night and day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What time was breakfast eaten, do you remember when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, we were easy-going, because my brother at that time was at the War, at that time when I remember very clearly and then he had to work away at different times, well, there was only Father and Mothe
r and I, we just did jolly well as we liked. If we wanted our breakfast at 9 we had it. If we were going anywhere we'd get up at 7 and have it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you eat normally all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Father and Mother and I always sat down together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What did you usually eat and drink for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
We had very good food, beautiful bacon and egg done in a Dutch oven in front of the kitchen fire, and Mother had lovely homemade bread and homemade marmalade. Everything was homemade. And we had quite a lot of company.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have anything different on certain days, like Sundays? Would you eat different things for breakfast on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, not necessarily. You could have what you wanted. And we always had sirloin on a Sunday, a lump of sirloin.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about the midday meal during the week, what time would you have that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
We always had a good dinner, and when I say a good dinner, I mean a good dinner, at 1 o'clock. And then we had tea at 4 and Mother never dirtied a pan after 4 o'clock, she wouldn't. That was the end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What would be an average sort of dinner, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, Monday we had the cold meat from the sirloin, which is beautiful and always loads left which the women took away to their homes when they'd done the cleanin
g, and that. Now Tuesday we always had fish not on Fridays. Wednesday we had a pie with a crust on, and on Thursday we had a meat pudding or a pot pie as they called them in the North.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What is a pot pie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 It's lovely, it's just like a meat pudding, steak and kidney and suet pudding, and we had that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And what did you have on a Friday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
On a Friday we generally had oxtail, it was made beautiful with forcemeat balls and Mother used to put Port wine in it. And if we didn't have oxtail we had
 pork when it was in season, but not when it was out of season. And then on Saturday I think we had a put-off dinner, what we called a 'tea dinner'
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What was that exactly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, maybe a big, thick rasher of ham done in the oven with eggs. I liked that dinner best of all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Tea at 4 o'clock we generally had bread, butter because we liked that best, scones, we always had fruit cake, and Mother was good at making tarts, all sorts of fruit tarts. The food was good then, and cheap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have anything else to eat at all before you went to bed?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
You could have what you liked, some more bread of cake, or sponge cakes and milk or cocoa, or whatever was going. What we wanted. You'd be asked what you wanted, and got it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Fancy being able to remember all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, I can see it. I can see the knives and forks on the table, and I can see Mother sitting at the top. And I can see Father sitting - and I liked to sit next to Father because he was very fond of me. I t
hink it was with being old, you know. And we had an old cleryman lived next door, a very clever man and he had a dog, Raddy, and they came, you know, to the old house and Mother said to Father 'when they come in for tea I don't want you to chew bread and 
g
ive it to the dog', because he had no teeth, this little dog, he'd worn them away. And so, of course, as soon as we were seated round the table Father started to chew the bread for the dog, and Mr. Smith, who was very cultured, he says 'Oh, Mr. Gardiner, 
I see ...' he said 'I have to do the same for my dog because it had no teeth, we're all in the same boat'. And they became such friends. They came in for tea 'till they died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You said that you had everything home made at home, did you mother bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
We didn't buy any cakes. She made lovely tea cakes, beautiful scones, and she was a beautiful cook. And her brown bread, oh, it was out of this world.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she make her own jam, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes. Jam, chut}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3015624\charrsid2560445 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 ey, marmalade, bottled fruit, the lot. We had cupboard loads.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And vegetables, did she bottle her own vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, never. We always had vegetables in the garden, they came on as you needed them, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about wine and medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Mother used to make herb beer which was as neat to the thing as ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Herb beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Herb beer. It was lovely. And we used to make raspberry vinegar which was good for your throat. We always had combs of honey if you had a sore throat you got honey out of the comb to cure it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you'd have that for a sore throat? Did they grow their own vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes, we had a garden and our own apples, gooseberries, tomatoes, rhubarb, apples, potatoes. And then, in the '14 War Father had an allotment where he grew 
beautiful stuff and anybody that hadn't an allotment or a garden, he used to bring barrowloads home and give them away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever have to buy any vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Very, very rare.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And did your mother ever buy tinned, or dried vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never. I don't think there were many tins of vegetables. The only tin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445 
ned stuff I remember was Nestle\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 s milk. Pears, we used to have Bartlet pears, and we used to have salmon, which was beautiful, but apart from that we had very little t
inned stuff, very little indeed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your father or mother keep any livestock for the family? Hens, or pigs or goats?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, during the '14 War father kept a dozen hens which laid us heaps of eggs. We were never short of eggs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But before that did you keep them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, no. We had a horse and a trap and dogs, but we didn't have any cows or sheep or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Who would look after the hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How many times a week did you eat meat? Now, you told me, in fact, didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Monday, cold ... Sunday sirloin; Monday, cold meat; Tuesday, fish; Wednesday, pie; Thursday, meat pudding, hot pie; Friday, often had pork or oxtail; Saturday, anything, ham or anything nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Six days a week you would ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, and the table was always properly set, tureens and the whole lot. We didn't just dish out of the pan like you do nowadays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you ever remember seeing your mother have less food so that the family could have more? You said you were well provided for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
You could have as much as you liked. If you wanted another helping you could have it. In fact, they were always pressing food on to you because they thought it was a necessary thing to eat well. But what was ever left over Margaret used to take home, 
or Mrs. Gibson would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But your mother never stinted herself in order that you could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, never! Oh, no! Of course, we weren't mean with anybody that helped because during the War Father would give them the good vegetables out of the allotment, eggs, and whatever we had. And if he knew anybody sick ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your father have a large appetite?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Very light appetite, very, very moderate eater, and never drunk anything. He wouldn't drink any alcohol at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were you allowed to talk during meals, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes. The mealtimes were the noisiest times of all. I think everybody talked, especially old Smithy when he was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And could you choose what you wanted to eat? You said 'just what you liked', you could choose? You weren't made to eat certain things?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, you had to eat fish on a Tuesday and pot pie on a Thursday, but if you didn't want to eat it up you could eat something else. It was always very nice, we just ate it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What would be your parents' attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, the dog just ate it, just put in on a plate. And if we didn't somebody else's dog was always coming in. The dogs knew, they would come in. And we had a seat outside the dining}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 room window, and the dining}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
room window was open in the summer, of course, and all the beggars knew if they came into our place and sat on that seat they'd get a dinner, and they did know, and they used to come. They took advantage of it, really. And of course, when the '14 W
ar came the food became scarce.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
When you were at table and there was something you wanted, like the salt, could you ask someone to pass it or did you have to wait until it was offered to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I think we just stretched over and got it, \{BLANK\} very good manners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you could have a second helping you said earlier, they were always pressing you to have a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes. In fact, you could scrape the pudding dish out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have to hold your knife and fork in a certain way and sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, yes, and Mother was ... she taught you how to use a soup spoon, not to drip it, or anything, you know. Oh, yes, she knew all the answers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Could you bring toys or a book to the table if you wanted to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We could, but we never did. We were interested in eating and then we had our toys and books and things after you had finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, my mother and father were easy. When there was just me ... of course, if you had compan
y you couldn't leave, but if we were alone you could just jump up in the middle of it and have a dance and sit down again. It was just very easy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you all sat at the table for the meal, the whole family sat at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, and every Sunday
 we had a half-wit from the workhouse to dinner and it didn't matter who came to dinner. Father said, 'now we can't tell Ned not to come'. He was very docile and he came every Sunday. I never remember sitting down on a Sunday without Ned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you always have the same place at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you always sat next to your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Where would Ned sit when he came?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Say the table was here, Father sat there and I sat here, Mother sat there and Ned sat there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Your father sat at the head of the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, Mother.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Your mother did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 She was boss.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 She was the boss?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 There's nobody boss, really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They were very easy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Who served the meal up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What order were you served in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, say I had to get back to school I suppose she gave me my dinner first. I went to school .... you went in at a quarter to nine and came out at one and you had to be for the day. It was a private school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember, by any chance, before you could feed yourself who would feed you? Can you remember that far back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
I remember, I must have been very little, and we used to have visitors come and Mother would sometimes send them down to the tramcar down the road and you w
ere always sure of Father giving you a spoonful of Nestles milk. And the little dog we had, he wouldn't go to bed until he got a teaspoonful of Nestle's milk. He had a tin of milk a week. See, we were an easy family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about the people that your mother employed? There was Mary Ellen, for instance. Now, where did she eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, Mary Ellen just ate with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 At the same table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about the ladies who came in to wash?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They sat with us at the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You all had food together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, and Father used to cut them the best. Gave them the best. They always got the best, never the second, and always served first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They would be served first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Father served them first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Very. She was Scottish. She left Scotland when she was 11 and she was as Scotch when she was 93. Never lose it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you found her easy to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes, she was very easy to talk to. Not about sex, we didn't talk about that!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 She wouldn't talk about sex?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she show affection? You said earlier that your brother didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, and Mother was Scottish and they're not ... they don't show affection. No, they don't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 If you had any worries could you share them with her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, to a certain extent. There was, maybe, some}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 things that worried you that you wouldn't say anything about in case it worried her. They weren't real worries, you know, just childish things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about your father, could you share your worries with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes, but as far as I can remember I hadn't any worries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And your father, was he an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Very.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And was he affectionate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, but very easy. Easy-going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did he ever cuddle you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, and nobody asked in vain. If they needed anything, it was given and forgotten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brother in a certain sort of way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, we just were natural, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about with other children. Say, for instance, another child hit you, would you be told to hit back, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, no. I don't think anybody hit me. I don't remember anybody hitting me ever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You know, the way children sometimes do. They fight, don't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No. And then, of course, having a business my brother was often down there. He liked to be where the men were working, you know, by the workers, and he liked to be there. There was more going ... we lived in a private house and it was very quiet, but he l
iked to be down where the upset was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, I don't think they had any ... they just wanted you to grow up ordinary and decent. You were taught what was right and what was wr
ong and if you did anything maybe wrong, that worried you a bit. But otherwise, they weren't strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did they consider that certain things were important in life? Did they tell you that certain things were important?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They thought the truth was 
important, and respect, and a good life was important which, I think, both my brother and I ... have never done much harm to anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 So they thought it was important, the truth and to be good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, you had to be ... we were naturally good, I th
ink. I suppose being brought up in a home like mine there was little opportunity to be bad. You never saw any bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What did they think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I never heard Father swear in his life, and I never heard my brother swear but once. Some of his 
models had gone wrong and he swore and Mother .... And no rude stories.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They weren't allowed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, and when my brother worked at the factory of course he used to ... and he would tell Mother but not Father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever hear your mother swear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Never! She had a favourite word, she used to say 'dash it all', that was all. Never heard her swear. I don't know whether that was a north country expression, 'dash it all'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 It's a southern one as well, I've heard it before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Have you? Dash it all, that was as far as it went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When grown-ups were talking when you were a child, were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I don't think anybody'd prevented us, but we never did, I was always a very good listener.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 If you did something that your parents disapproved of, what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, they would say they didn't like that way of doing it, or saying it, or that way of going on, and that would be the end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They didn't punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never! I was never punished in my life!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never once?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never once! Never. Never. We'd be threatened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But not actually punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents, or did one play a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Mother was, maybe, stricter, but that's not the word because she wasn't strict ; but Father was the gentler of the two. He was never nasty. Mother could maybe be sarcastic, but Father was gentle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Which of the two do you think, if you had to say, influenced you more?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, Father. In fact, I wasn't terribly fond of Mother, why I don't know. She was a very ... she was an ideal mother, but Father was a warmer and ... I don't know what it was. He was a kindly man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Perhaps it was being an only daughter, too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Maybe, I don't know. And on a Friday I always used to go to the sale room with him to see furniture auctions which was ... I loved it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, you could 
ask ... I had quite a few friends, close friends, and Mother would make ... for one thing, she always made a special, a custard cake. I don't know why she on another day. It was round, it was full of custard. And my friend Ena was very fond of custard cak
e
 so this birthday she made one and she put it in the yard to cool, you see, and when we loved out there was about 5 and 20 blackbirds all sitting round and they picked every bit of custard out. So we didn't have any custard cake. She said 'talk about 'Sin
g a Song of Sixpence'!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have anything else made for you special to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. (doubtfully)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, presents, but we didn't have a lot of toys through the year, unless friends gave them to you. And I remember, I
 had my tonsils out and when I was getting better there was an old couple lived down the road and they brought me a lovely pair of skipping ropes, with tartan handles. Loved them. And those two funny old maids, Wilson, they called them, they brought me a 
lovely pair of scales. They were like that, with little weights. They were good ones. And then this old ... Mr. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6111701 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
 Mrs. Thompson, when I got on to me feet they brought a carriage, a hired one, and I remember - Mr. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6111701 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  Mrs. Thompson were old, they sat, like, he
re and I was sitting there and oh, it was lovely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you go out for a drive?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes, took us all round for a drive in the carriage. Two horses, and they pulled the old carriage, and if it came on to rain there was a hood, but it was a fine day, it didn't come on to rain.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I bet you loved that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, I loved that. I can remember it as though it was yesterday, walking and getting in the carriage, you know. And old Mrs. Thompson with her parasol up; whether the sun was shining I wouldn't know, but I think she always had the parasol up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Can you remember anything you did with your mother or father together on Christmas Day? Can you remember what a Christmas Day would be like?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes. We had a dinner, turkey and ginger wine - no alcohol in our house, not that they were prejudiced at all, or \{BLANK\}
 or anything. We had a cup of tea and then we all got dressed and went up to Uncle Tom's for Christmas Night and had a lovely spread. They had a beautiful house and Meggie was an aristocrat and she was ... oh, it was a beautiful spread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have a party up there? Was it like a sort of family party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, because Uncle Tom had a lot of, you know, sons and daughters. And they had a window, like that, but it was deep, and some of the
 boys the older ones, used to black their faces and get behind the curtain and then we had a show. And they were lovely parties.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you always went to your Uncle Tom's at Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Uncle Tom's, 'till he died. And Uncle Tom and Aunt Meggie had
 been out in Africa and in those days it was primitive, you know, and they'd brought a lot of trophies home, and ... It was a warm house. It was warm, and there was flowers and fruit, and there was warmth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 That's a lovely feeling, isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I ca
n feel it yet. There isn't that today, you know. I think people of my age lived in the better day, but if you were poor, you were poor! Ooh, it was hard for the poor people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 In your home did you have any musical instruments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We had a piano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Who played the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, I was taught. I was never very good but I could ... you know, play a tune to please anybody. And we had friends who could play, and they used to play and sing and have a really good time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your mother or father play the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, but Father could play anything by ear, which he often did. Mother had no ear at ... I don't think she knew God Save The Queen from damn. No, she didn't. She wasn't musical.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about singing, was there anyone who sang in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. Father was a nice singer, but he just sang. Just sang, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, just when he felt like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When he felt like it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever get together and make music as a family? You said he'd pick out tunes on the piano. Would y
ou ever stand round the piano and ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, but mostly with friends. When we 3 were together there wasn't much music.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 It would be when friends came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, friends who were maybe more musical than we were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
They were interested in what you were doing. Father was a good tennis-player and he liked to play cricket. Mother didn't play anything. She was always busy cooking and doing other things. She wasn't lazy, but she didn't go and play tenn
is, or ... But Father used to like a game of tennis, or cricket.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were there books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, plenty of books.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, every night we got the Evening Chronicle. Not on a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We 
used to get 'The People's Friend', 'The Sunday Circle', 'The Sunday Companion', and 'Early Days' for me. And 'Home Chat' and there was Jungle Jinks at the back, and as soon as we got The Home Chat, of course, Mother used to sit down and read us Jungle Jin
k
s. It was an elephant and a monkey and ... Jungle Jinks. That was the highlight of the week and we got them on a Friday night. We went down into the village and mother would ask ... she got her books, 'The Circle' and 'The Sunday Companion', 'The People's
 
Friend', and 'Home Chat' which had Jungle Jinks in it and bring them home. And you could get a very nice penny book which was very nicely ... but for 1 penny and it was ... she used to get a Bible story, you see, Joseph and his brethren, and Moses in the 
bulrushes, and ... all stories of the Bible. And one day we were in the paper shop and she said to Gordon and I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
'What would you like tonight? Would you like this .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember your mother or father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes, they were both great readers. Yes, they read anything and everything
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did they ever read aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, Mother had to read to Father 'cos he was so lazy. He liked her to read to him, and Mr. Smith, old Smithy, he used to read 2 hours every night to his wife.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 He was the parson next door?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 He was a beautiful reader and he knew it. Yes, he loved it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But your mother read to your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes. We used to read him 'The Sunday Circle' and everything; 'Home Chat', everything that came in
, she just got ... And she read the paper out to him, and ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And she read to you, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember a funeral in the family when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I remember nothing else, we were such a big family we were always
 having a funeral. Mother once went into black and she was in black for 5 years. We had a big family. Father ... there were 14 of them. Well, sure to be some of them dying, either wives, or ... And then Mother had a big family, there were 7 of them. Oh, w
e had funerals, certain, but we never went. In the north only men go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And what about children, when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, no, we saw funerals passing, but we never went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 It's just the men that went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, women didn't go. It used to be 
a bit of a poppy show, you know, a funeral. It was a day out. And you had a very ... tremendous spread if you went went back to the people's house. And if any of your acquaintances died you went to the funeral, I think it was out of respect, or something,
 which you wouldn't do now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about mourning clothes, what were they like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Black. And when Grandfather died, Mother's father ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How old were you then, when your grandfather died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I would be about 5, four or 5. And Grandma was a ve
ry handsome woman and she knew it, and she came and she had crepe round her bonnet and a little bit of white under here, and she had a black mantle lined with squirrel and all down there was crepe and it was most beautiful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, and I remember her. And she said 'Mercy me, I've had n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  compliment paid to me this day'. Mother said 'have you no'?' She says, 'I was coming up in the tramcar and a little girl said to her mother "there's Queen Victoria"', she says 'I'm glad I'm not 
like her' (laughter). She thought it was no compliment, a little stodgy thing like her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What did the men wear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, when Father went to a funeral he had a frock coat and a silk hat, and that was all. They were really nicely dressed, with nice w
hite linen, but not ostentatious and the most ...}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445  walked ... walked behind the hearse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 , you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How long would people stay in mourning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, a whole year. Yes, if your sister or your mother ... it was a whole year, in fact. And then half-mourning
 for another year, I think. I think they followed the example of the late Queen, Queen Victoria. You know, it was an age of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445 hypocrisy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 , of course. They were great hypocrites. I think they were. It was quite a permissive age, but it wasn't published. I think
 so, because, after all, Nature's just the same as it's always been, since Adam and Eve it hasn't changed; cloaked over, yes, but that ... Of course, you never thought of that when you were a child, but after you grew up you began to see a bit through it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When you were a child were you taken out visiting neighbours and friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes, we used to go out for tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Who would take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Mother, I used to go with Mother, and we used to ... you know, get really washed and dressed. But just t
ea, and we had a nice tea. Several friends we had, and then they would come to our house, and then we would be back about 6, we didn't stay the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Just for tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, just for tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And were you taken shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 With your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes, we always went shopping. We went to Newcastle. We went shopping and we went in for tea, and early cup of tea, and as a great treat we used to have a cream horn. That was a treat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever go out with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I was mostly always with Father. In fact, when I started to go out with Alec it hurt him, he felt out of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But when you were a child he took you out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Always. I was always sitting in the trap ... People used to know the time by us passing,
 this old man with the little girl. Because he looked older in those days, a man of 45 or 50 looked old then, but they don't look old today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember any other outings with your parents, Bank Holidays or any special outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 There was a b
ig festival on the Town Moor, a very big moor, and there was roundabouts and shows and freaks and all sorts of things. And we used to go there on a race week. There was racing at Gosforth Park near Newcastle, and then we ... We didn't go to the racing but
 we would go to what we call the Moor and have a go on the water, shooting, and one thing and another and enjoy it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What time of the year was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Race week was in June, about the middle of June.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you go every year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Every year. I can't ever remember missing it. And then when I got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  we used to take the children and the dog and we used to walk round. It was huge. And they had their caravans and all their families and the dogs tethered under the things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
I did, because as I was telling you Chats had a lovely country house at Rothbury in Northumberland and we used to go there, and we used to have a sort of cab to the station and then we used to get unloaded and get into the train and g
et out at Rothbury. It was beautiful. And Mrs. Chatt had a niece my age, we enjoyed ourselves. And then I used to go with my friend up to Bamborough. But Mother and Father didn't care to go away, they liked their own home. Never went away to stay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They didn't take you to the seaside or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, I used to go to Alnmouth. I got more holidays than most, but it was always with friends. I had two aunts, the one that died here and my other one, and they used to take us to Alnmouth a lovely seaside place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How long would you go for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 A fortnight. Two weeks, that was the limit. Never 3, 2.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What would you do on holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, I was rather limited because I seemed to be always with aunties there, and I'd have much preferred to have a few school}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 friends, but I was with elderly people on those holidays.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What sort of things would you do with your aunts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, we would walk and we would take a picnic and sit on the beach and paddle in the sea, or bathe in the sea;
 or maybe walk to a neighbouring town and have a look at the shops and see what was different in a neighbouring town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And when you went to stay with Mrs. Chattswith your friend what did you do then on holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, they were solicitors and they
 were rather ... what you might call 'posh', but they had risen and they'd got rather a lot of swank, more swank than we had, but they were ordinary people who had risen, and this house ... we took ... Lizzie, she was a little maid they had, a maid of all
 work, and Haggie, the dog, they all went and we used to fish in the Coquet, go for walks and Lizzie used to take us right up the hills and pick bilberries and go down the village and ... just waste our time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Can you tell me how you spent Saturdays when you were a child, in the first house you had in Beaconsfield Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, well, my grandma lived at Gateshead and it was through Saltwood Park, and then ... Mother and I used to walk through the park and then Grandma lived through the gate at the othe
r side, and then we used to come home, walk back home. And then we used to go to the shop and come home with Father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Would it be teatime on Saturday, or would it be later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, a little later, more like 7 or eightish o'clock. Because shops kept o
pen until 11 or 12 at night, you know, they didn't close very early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, we used to go to Sunday School, and we used to go to the Weslyan Chapel on a Sunday morning with Father's sisters, that ... two of those. Aunt Ellen used to stop at home and cook a big dinner, and then we had our dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your mother and father go to Church as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Not in the morning, in the evening. And then we used to go in the evening to Church and then for a walk and then just come ho
me for our supper. And that was our Saturday and Sunday, then it was the round again, back to school on Monday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have different clothes at the weekends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes, we had our best clothes and you didn't put them, best clothes on on a Saturday or a Friday; always on a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you play games at the weekend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, we did. We had a big garden and we had a swing. We used to play 'shops' with the leaves and things, you know, not the fantastic toys you get now, and ... Yes, we used t
o get our time for dinner. We used to play ... oh, dear me ... hitching off the stones, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, I know, with a stick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, we used to hop ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, Hopscotch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, 'Tid, Mid, River Ray, Carlon, Palm, Paste Egg, Day, Set a cup upon
 a rock, Mask Meg on a Pot', and if you got up to the pot that was a score. Quite a simple game.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 That's unusual, I haven't heard those words before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 'Tid, Mid, River Ray, Carlon, Palm, Paste Egg, Day, Set a cup upon a rock, Mask Meg on a Pot'. That was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about Sundays, were you allowed to play on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, no, you didn't ... We were. Some people were very strict and you hadn't to ... you could read or ... but it was more of a day set apart for peace ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your parents think it was wrong to work on a Sunday? Or to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
They didn't think it was wrong to play, you could go out and play, but I don't think we did, much. It was more of a day apart. The horse never worked on a Sunday, wouldn't take you out for a drive o
n a Sunday, the horse had to rest. He had a day of rest and gladness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you like it, did you enjoy Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, immensely. Immensely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And your parents went to the Weslyan Chapel in the evening, did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 So they were Wesleyan?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes. John Wesley, you've heard of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, I have, indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
He stayed with my grandmother, I think it was on about 40 occasions, and I've still got the teapot he used to drink out of, and my brother got his chair, John Wesley's chair.
 And I got the little teapot from Aunt Janet, which I still have. He got old and Grandma thought, well, the old boy can't come down the stairs, we'll take a cup of tea up to him. And she said he was a very fastidious man and he was rather proud. He never 
appeared without his buckles on and his diamond ring. He was very foppish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you go with your parents to Church on Sunday evening, to Chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 So you went in the morning and in the afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And the Sunday School was in the morning, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, in the afternoon. You met a lot of people ... And then, on a Sunday evening we used to all go to Aunties house, Father's sisters, because there were 3 not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 , and a lot of people went, it was more like a public house than a private one. They used to what you'd call 'beat up' and we'd discuss, making plans for another week, and it was nice. I liked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What does it mean 'beat up', exactly?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, a 'beat up' is when a tribe meets all mates; uncles and cous
ins. We used to have all the news of the week and what was going on next week, what was done and what we were going to do, and it was all very pleasant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And in your Sunday School - going back to that a minute - were there any Sunday School outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, that was the highlight of the year!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What happened on a Sunday School outing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
We went in the train, we all walked down to the train. Mother went with us, and Father, and a lot of wealthy people went because it was a wealthy Church. And we used to go to \{BLANK\}
 Castle, and you could look through the Castle, you could play in the grounds. There was races and there was skipping and all sorts of sports, you know, to please kids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Once a year you went, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Once a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were there any other social activities organized by the Chapel that you took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
There was concerts and bazaars and all sorts of things. And it was a community, and it was nice. It was lovely. The bazaars were beautiful. There was all the stalls and 
the fruit stalls and flowers and that lovely smell; and then all the tables were set and you paid so much for your tea. And then there'd be a big concert at the last thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, I was no singer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did the Chapel run any temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 There was a Band of Hope, used to rescue the perishing, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were you a member of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We used to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What exactly did they do, this Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Often there used to be a magic lantern, and Mr. Youn
g used to put a hymn on, 'What a Friend We Have In Jesus', or something, and we used to all sing it. And Mother once went and she says 'Never again! Oh!', she says, 'The smell of dirty kids, I'm not going there again' (laughter). She wouldn't go back.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you belong to any other club organized by the Chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, dear. And then the Presbyterians came and built a tent chapel at the Back of our house, the first house in Beaconsfield Road, and then it was nice and near and I used to go there because 
my friends, they were members, so I rather forsook my Chapel and went to the Presbyterian Church. They had a young family, there was Maurice, Margaret, Charlie and Freddie. Freddie was at ... for years he was at ... is it Frogmore up at Hampstead?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Frognal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Frognal. How it's funny. Mrs. Hewison said to me 'now call at the china shop along Beauchamp Place and you can get cheap china', and I went and the girl says 'where do you come from?' 'Well,' I says, 'I come from the North', and she says, 'so d
o I'. She says, 'We lived at Ashington'. She was quite... she didn't look old. I said, 'Did you know Freddie Simmonds?' 'Oh,' she says, 'he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  me, you know, he was the minister'. Well, I says, 'I wondered where he was because he's not at Frognal', bec
ause I used to see it on the board, I used to sometimes to the Frognal, he made a big fuss and I'd go back and have tea with him and what not, and, I says, 'I've lost touch, 'I says, 'I thought he must be dead'. 'Oh, no,' she says, 'his wife died and he's
 got a big church at Bournemouth now and enjoying hisself'.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 So you used to go to the clubs organized by the Presbyterian Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, and Mrs. Simmonds was a charming woman, we loved her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Was Grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, 
my Uncle Tom - he was a good man, but he was a wag; he used to say 'Oh, God, make us able to eat everything on this table. That was the Grace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But your mother and father didn't say Grace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, no. We were very thankful. And Uncle Tom had a big fa
mily and they were all at home at the weekend, because they went to work and one thing and another, but at the weekend ... and they had this beautiful dining table and a lovely room, and all used to stand up and sing 'Be present at our table, Lord', once 
a week. And then, when the meal was finished they all used to sing 'Thank God from whom all blessings flow'. But they weren't sanctimonious with it, it was from the heart they sang.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And was it on Sundays they sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Just on Sundays, once a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, when we were small we used to say our prayers at the bedside. As we got bigger I think we forgot about them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When you were a child you did say them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, always. We were always taught ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, never. My father didn't believe in them, he says that was a private ... something private between a person and his Lord, he didn't believe in family prayers. That was carrying too far, no one ever had family prayers, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your father take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Not very much, but he was really what you'd call a rank Conservative. But Uncle Tom was a Socialist, that was a long time ago, and of course, Father and he used to argue.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Why do you think your father was a rank Conservative?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Because I think, perhaps, he had property and that and maybe he thought it was worth fighting for if it came to the push. He was a socialist because he gave such a lot away, but he didn't believe in givi
ng everything away. Given in proportion. He wouldn't have liked it taken from him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about your mother, did she have an interest in politics?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. No, Mother didn't mind whether people were Catholics or what they were, as long as they were de
cent folk she never worried what their religion was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Political attitudes, too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she ever say she was a Conservative, or ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, I think she would maybe be influenced by Father. But in those ... Mother's young days there was no vote.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Quite, not for women.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, it was after that, and I remember the Law being annulled ... I was very little and this Mr. Chatts was a solicitor and I used to sit on Father's knee and I used to hear them discussing things, and they used
 to ... discussed this Law ... You know at one time if I had 3,000 or 30,000 or 130,000, the minute you were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
 that became the husband's and you were his and he could spit on you, tread on you, but it had been ... they got it annulled and I remember it being annulled and their saying what a good thing it was, because it wasn't fair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And your father thought it was a good thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, well, Mother had no money but had she had money my father wouldn't have wanted it. But there was men who took 
the lot and were very bad to their wives, so I was led to believe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember your father or mother voting in a general election? before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, they always voted. They went up to the school, as we do today and we wore red for the Conservative, or Tory ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Red for Tory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Red for Tory and blue for Liberal. There was no socialist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And your father voted for ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Red.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Always red?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Red.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes. But other people that were Liberals, of course, wore blue.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Now, in some places at that time men felt they risked losing their job or their house if they voted differently from their employers. Your father was self-employed, wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, he was his own boss, always?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But do you think he felt himself under any kind of pressure to vote one way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, no, no, no. And I remember - say, you were a servant of Lord Ravensworth, who lived pretty near, and Lord Durham, the Earl of L and what have you ... I think there was pressure on them t
o vote to keep the Conservatives in power. They didn't even want the Liberals to have any power, but the Liberals were getting a big hold just before the first World War. I think - mind, that's only my idea, I might be completely wrong.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Was your father actually a member of the Tory Party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, you didn't ... you weren't members, you just voted, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember him working for the Tory party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your parents take part in any political activity other than at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When your parents were doing their work how did they spend their time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They were always together, you know, they used to go for a walk over the golf course; and they used to go long wa
lks; and sometimes Father would yoke the horse and they'd go for a drive, and that was just ... there was nothing much to do. They were very happy. I never, in all my life heard my mother say 'I'm fed up, I'm browned off', or 'I'm bored' because she never
 was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she have any other interests outside the home, herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, no, she had her friends, and she was very quick-witted and funny and ... No, she was never bored, never fed up. Never up the wall, or round the bend or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she ever go out to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
She was always enjoying herself. She did nothing else but enjoy herself. You see, Father was on the spot and we were just a very close community, and one enjoyed the company of another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 She didn't do anything sort of special, just for herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
She didn't do any charitable work, or anything. She didn't sew for bazaars or ... She didn't do anything, really. She just lived for Father and they were quite happy together. Just pottered about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When did your father get home from work in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, he just used to come up at any time because he had a good manager in the shop and sometimes he'd pop in at 3 and say 'well go here', or pop in at 2 and say 'we'll go that', and we had a dog, a black
 and tan terrier, Jip, and every time, ... you know, we had a trap, 2 sat in front and 2 behind, and every time Jip saw Father get the Brasso out and polish that silver rim he'd flew breathless up to tell Mother and me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 It's time to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And Moth
er says 'Oh, you'd better get your hat on or Father will be coming'. Then we used to go for a nice drive round Finkle Abbey, some little place; Durham, often. It was quite nice.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How many evenings a week would he spend at home? Did he ever go out in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never. In all his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
 life he only had his dinner once out of his own home, and he hated it. He didn't enjoy it. One Sunday he went to Morpeth with his brother to see a friend and he was miserable. That was the only time he had his dinner out of his own home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You told me earlier he never went to a pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Or a club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. Didn't believe in those, but he didn't stop you from going if you'd wanted it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did he take part in any sport? You said earlier that he played tennis,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes, he used to go along to the Cricket Club at night, Mother used to go with him and he used to have a game, Mother used to sit and talk to the womenfolk. And then, in the tennis season he used to have a round or two of tennis, and Mot
her would sit again, talking to the womenfolk. Father would have a game and then we just came home and had our supper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did he ever go to the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, never!! He was fond of horses, but he never went to the races. Or never put a bet on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did he think it was wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, he must have thought it wasn't right. But he wasn't a prejudiced man, if you wanted to go to the races you could go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your mother or father belong to any savings club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 It was one perpetual save. He saved and saved and retired with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6111701 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 600 a year in 1912. That was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6111701 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
12 a week, which was an awful lot of money, 'cos the average wage was 27/- to 35/- a week. And a bank manager had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6111701 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
5 a week in 1912, and he retired with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6111701 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 600 a year. He saved ... well, he was a good speculator and a good ... he had property.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did he actually put it into a club, though, or did he ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 He didn't belong to any clubs against sickness or funerals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, we always could pay our way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 He put it into the bank, did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 He invested it, he lived on the interest, which I'm still living on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How did you get on with your brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Splendidly. Splendidly. We never had a wrong word.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you feel very close to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, and ... henie is a word we
 used in the North, and Gordon was always afraid of the dark. He is still, you know. It's funny, he has a sort of a feeling, you know, of the spirit world, I think, he never says anything: and we had an attic right up at the top of the house, naturally, a
n
d if he wanted anything out of the attic when it was dark - we had no lights to switch on - he used to say, 'little Henie, go and get that out of the attic'. And I used to trundle away up because I wasn't afraid of the dark. But he said, 'little Henie, go
 up and get this', or 'get that' or the other, and I used to do it. No, we never had a wrong word.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When you were little did you play with him a lot, or did you have a lot of ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, he had a lot of boy friends, kids, you know. I remember their names.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
There was an Edith Henderson, an Ena Thompson, Peggy Donald, quite a few little girls, from school, you know. I used to bring them home for their tea or you'd bring somebody home on a Sunday from Sunday School, whic
h were not quite so classy as the everyday ones, you know, but it didn't worry me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Where did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
In the garden, and sometimes we'd ... our favourite walk was to walk through the churchyard and look at the tombstones. Oh, it was, and read them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever play in the street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, it didn't ... my brother had a bike and the streets weren't busy and we used to along ... he used to have a bike and I used to stand on the back, and maybe another boy would race along backwards and forwards, a wide road but there was no traffic.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What sort of games did you play? You told me about that game with the rhyme.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes. Mostly ... of course, we had a good swing, we used to swing on that. And we used to play honey pots.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What's honey pots?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
You stood in a row, you're all honey pots, and if any boy chose you, they'd have to lift the honey pot away. And we used to play statues, you had to guess who you were ; and colours, I was a colour, you were a colour and the one that was guessi
ng had to guess the colour and the one that was left was left in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes, you could get dirty, and you could get washed again. Oh, Mother never minded if you got dirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were you free to play with anyone that you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Anyone you liked. I could bring anybody in, whether they were miner's kids or ... well, Leonard Wilson, the Bishop of Birmingham used to come in. His father was chaplin of the Newcastle jail.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 There were no certain children that your parents discouraged you to play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, they didn't dislike any kids, it didn't matter. who they were. No, they weren't snobs.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Now, I think we got up to where I was asking you about the games you played and you told me about 
them. Did you belong to any youth organizations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
There wasn't youth organizations then. We used to go to Sunday School and we sometimes had a concert and we used to all beat up there and put the concert on. And there was a Band of Hope which we used 
to go to for a lark. We once took Mother and she said she couldn't abide the smell of it so she never went again. Those sort of things, but there were no youth ... oh, there were Scouts and things, but I wasn't ... belonged to any organisation whatsoever.
 There was more Church organisations, but ... you know, little meetings for the younger ones, but not like they have now, not youth clubs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I'd like to ask you about how you spent your free time when you were at school. Did you have any hobbies then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No. I went to a very nice school, Escombe House. It was a ... not a lot of scholars. But we didn't have any hobbies. We went at 9 o'clock to evade the Board school children, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They weren't nice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We thought they weren't nice, but they 
were and turned out very well, a lot of them, better than the other schools. And we went ... and then we came out at 1, but we didn't go back any more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I see, just went in the mornings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Mornings, but t'was from 9 'till 1, it wasn't half past 8. 
Nine 'till 1. No, we went at half past nine, 'till 1 o'clock, but we learnt as much in those hours as though we'd been there all day. But we had no hobbies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you keep any pets? You had a dog, you told me, a black Labrador. Can you remember any other pets you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We always had pets. Father or Mother never minded what pet you brought in, it was cared for and looked after and made one of the family.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Can you remember the pets that you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Jip was the one I can remember most because it
 was a very wise little dog; it could open gates and it could kill rats, it could do anything, and that stands out in my mind. Also a very small Yorkshire terrier. But apart from that we had a lot of pets, they never minded you having ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have always have a cat or a dog?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Not a cat. Dogs, horses, and other people brought their pets when they went away, Father and Mother never went away, and we had a parrot and other people's things to keep. We always kept them for neighbours, so we general
ly had plenty of pets in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you collect anything, you know the way some children collect things, did you make a habit of collecting anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, I collected books, a lot of books I collected. I never let them go out of the home. The
re are still a lot there in the bookcase, now. And my brother collected birds' eggs. Father in those days collected antiques and I spent a lot of time in sale rooms with my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Helping him buy his things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, we fancied the same things an
d he was getting older by then, you see, and we did spend quite a lot of time on a Friday in the sale rooms in Newcastle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How old would you have been then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, I'd maybe be ... from about 12 years old 'till I met my husband. We went every Friday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you do any gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No. Father had a lovely garden and that's one thing he didn't like us to touch. You'd pick your flowers, but he didn't like you to mess in his garden. That was his hobby, his garden, and we kept away from that. We enjoyed it without labouring in it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Never. But I used to go with neighbours, they had a country house at Rothbury, a beautiful place, and the Coquet runs through Rothbury and they were great fishers, and I used to go out with them and we used to fish for trout.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 The River Coquet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 The River Coquet, up in Northumberland. Beautiful place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever go for walks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We did nothing else but go for walks, there's nothing else to do. We had to take the dogs for
 a walk and we had to ... we always went for walks, every day of our life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Who would you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Father. Or, maybe, a friend, but more often Father, because we had a lot in common. We liked the same things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about bicycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, 
I hadn't a bicycle, he was too scared you'd get killed. My brother had a bike, and that. But I generally went with Father, and he generally had a horse and a trap. We called it a 'turn-out'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 A 'turn-out'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 It was a 'turn-out'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Is that the horse and trap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 The trap. It was a nice turn-out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, no. There was a nice tennis ground and a cricket ground that we used to go and watch them play, but I didn't join. They were older people than I was, and 
we used to get the tea ready and when the games were finished we'd serve tea. It was quite a family affair and was very enjoyable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you go to any theatres? Or concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, we went to plenty of concerts. But we were Methodists, or Wesleyans,
 and they were against theatres. I never knew what for and if I did go with my aunties I mostly said I was somewhere else, if I went to the theatre. And then, when I got older I used to go with friends. Father and Mother never went to theatres.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But you did go to concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, we went to concerts. We went to hear Clara Butt and ... oh, very nice concerts, they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about music halls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Ooh, you hadn't to go to music halls!!! That was the Devil's playground!! You hadn't to go! It w
as forbidden!!! You must not go to music halls!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You never went to one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never!!!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about cinemas, when you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, when ... yes, we used to go to cinemas and they were very flickery in those days, it was like rai
n all the time, but it got better and better. But we did go to the cinema once a week on a Monday night, the washing night of all nights.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Just the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, Mother and Father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Mother and Father as well? I see. Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Very little. You got well fed, well clothed, you'd have what you liked but they didn't give you money. You got what you wanted but you never had anything in your pocket. They paid for everything and were generous to a degree but the
y never overstepped the mark at lavishing money on you or very good gifts. You got nice things and we had a lovely home, but not money or anything like that. I don't know why. I think everybody was the same, you know. Got a little bit at Christmas, and if
 friends came they'd give you a shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What would you spend it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I think we'd mostly spend it on sweets, or any trifling thing you fancied, you know, and made up your mind to get.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Can you remember what sort of sweets they were then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Mostly ... the best sweets were Terry's, and they were hard sweets and they were lovely sweets. My favourites were Satinettes, you never see them now but they were lovely. And there was really good toffee, and I remember when MacIntosh first brought his
 toffee out and it was beautiful and we used to buy a quarter of a lb. Extravagant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How much would that have cost?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, I should think it would be four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 pence a quarter, at the most.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did anyone outside the home help your mother look after the house? I remember, last time you told me there was a lady.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Mary, was she called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Margaret.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Was she the only person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, we had several, you know, coming in to help. There was a washerwoman, you know, she used to do the washing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did relations or friends or neighbours ever help your mother out in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
If anybody was ill I had a very efficient aunt, she used to nurse you 'till you were better. And of course, all the relatives came if you were ill to see how y
ou were, and our house was more like a public house than a private one because they just used to come in, it was such a big family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about neighbours and friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We had splendid neighbours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And they would come and help your mother sometimes, if anything was wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, Mrs. Chatt would. We had a solicitor on one side, a parson on the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Mr. Smith, wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, Mr. Smith; and a doctor, so we were all right. We didn't have many bills to pay in those ways, we were a
ll right. Very good neighbours, but I think we were good neighbours to them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How would you help them out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How would I help them out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, your family, would your family help out? Say, if the doctor next door was unwell, or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 P
oor Mother, if any of the doctor's family were ill she had to go because they were no use. Not a bit. She had to go whenever she was called. And, if anybody died she had to go and put the white stockings on, lay them out. I don't know why they came for he
r. She was very efficient.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 So, if your mother was ill your family would come, and particularly one aunt who was very good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, Father's sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What was she called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Jerry, Aunt Jerry, and she was very efficient, and she was a nice per
sonality. You felt better the minute she came in. If you knew Aunt Jerry was on the stairs you knew it was all right. You had no more fear after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How nearby did your relations live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They were nearly ... we had relations nearly in every stre
et, about 4 streets. They were only a street away. Now, I had one Uncle Tom and Aunt Meggie and they lived in Springfield Terrace and that was at the top of a hill, and we always called those 'the people on the hill', or 'on the bank'.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And I remember you telling me you had 3 aunts who lived together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, 3 old maiden aunts. Three unclaimed blessings. (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What a lovely expression! Now, it seems a silly question to ask because you've said that your parents had a lot of friends. Where 
did they see their friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 In their homes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They went to visit each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, yes, they did a lot of visiting, and a lot of ... not a lot of parties, but occasionally a party, and they all gathered. And of course, if there was a wedding o
r a funeral there was a 'beat up' there. And in the summer we all used to go a-picnic, all the young ones and the old ones, we all went together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Your parents' friends and their children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, my cousins and aunts and what have you, we went to a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445 
 picnic if it was a fine summer }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 day. Pack a big basket and Hubert and Gordon, my brother and a cousin, carried the basket and we had a nice time at the picnics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your mother and father share the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They would have the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes. They never had friends apart from themselves, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Your mother didn't have any friends of her own, special friends of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, they were Father's special friends, too. You see, they were all friends ... f
ather didn't meet any outsider on the side, or did Mother. They all came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I see, very close knit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Very close. You see, it was a regular thing, that. It ... didn't have a lot of outsiders.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were friends often invited into the house? Actually invited in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, they came, they'd drop in, but sometimes they were invited, then they had a special spread for them if it was something important.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How often would you say you had a ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We had close friends in every Sunday. And Father had 
a friend that he'd had from when he was a boy and he was mentally deficient but he wasn't dangerous and he always came every Sunday from the workhouse and had dinner with us, and I never remember sitting down on a Sunday without Ned coming up from the wor
k
house. And he used to frighten me, Ned, sometimes. But he was all quite harmless and I can remember when he was dying, going down to the workhouse to see Ned and both Mother and I remember how well cared for he was in the workhouse. Very well cared for. T
hey weren't such awful places as you are led to believe. This one was very nice, warm fired, warm beds and reasonably good food.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 That is interesting, because people get the idea that a workhouse was a terrible place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, you needn't ... Mother u
sed to say, 'well, you need never be frightened of the workhouse', because it was homely, it was clean and the old men used to talk together and they had their tobacco, and they had what we took them in. And Ned died. And they always allowed us to take ou
t
 dogs in to Ned and the old men loved to see these dogs. And we had one - I think we found Ginger, he must have been in the circus - he used to jump over every bed, up the middle and down again, which amused all the old fellows in there. They used to look
 forward to Mother and I going because we took some nice stuff to eat. But we had no horror of the workhouse because we say how well they were kept. So it's no use saying they were horrible places, this one was not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did friends call in casually without an invitation? You said they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And neighbours did, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And your parents went out to visit friends and neighbours, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 People often tell us that in those days they made their own am
usements, when you were a child this is. What do you think your parents did when they got together with their friends and neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Mostly, talk, and they were very good conversationalists, both Mother and Father, and their friends. They were profe
ssional people and they were never short of good talk. Never. And we sat round a good fire and threw the ball one to the other in conversation. You could all speak together or you could all speak in turn, and they could speak about anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did they make music together ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes, yes. Yes, they were musical. Piano and singing. It was very good quality, too, not a lot of rubbish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about games, would they ever play games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. They didn't play cards because that was one of the de
vil's tricks, you know. Cards, you mustn't touch cards. Not Wesleyans, didn't. Yes, we had games. And we used to dance, somebody played the piano and we used to dance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Would your parents dance as well, and their friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes, but just Sir Roger and maybe a waltz and a polka, and get quite happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Sir Roger de Coverly, that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes. And the Lancers. Yes, we used to have a dance, clear the room and dance. It was all so warm and homely, but at the same time a lot of people were very poor and hard up and lacked a lot of things. They did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Many people divide society into different social classes or groups. In that time, before 1918, did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. I remember, we were Wesl
eyans, but if the Catholics had a bazaar we always went; or the Church of England. We weren't bigoted to keep to one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 That's a religious division, but what about social divisions, sort of class divisions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, there was class divisions? And a very obvious class division.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Can you describe what it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, there were some had their ... We had a smart turn-out; a good pony and a good trap, two at the front and two at the back. But there was a class who had their carriage and one horse, a
nd there was the other class who had a carriage and a pair of horses and a coachman. They were above us, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And what about people who were less well off than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, they had nothing. In fact, they didn't have anything at all. And \{BLANK\}
, where I lived, it was a pit district. Lowfell wasn't, but they had to walk through Lowfell to get to what they call the Betty Pit and different pits and they wouldn't let them on the tramcar because they were dirty, so they had to walk miles. And when 
they got underground they had to walk miles back to where they worked, and they used to come home really dead tired and black, and for very little, very little indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How many social classes would you say there were in that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, it's dif
ficult. There was definitely the upper class, and there was definitely the class that was right on the bottom, that was found in the pubs drinking on a Friday and Saturday night and were never well off. Where the thrifty ones got on, bought a little bit o
f property, and you could advance not very much but you could advance. Even people who worked in the pit, there were ambitious ones and they got on and bought their own property.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Which sort of class or group would you say that you belonged to yourself at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, I would say that we were lower middle class, wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Father retired when he was 54 on a very good income, so we weren't
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What sort of people belonged to the other classes that you've mentioned? Y
ou talked about yourself as belonging to the lower middle class and then there was the upper class, and below you the very poor working people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes. But there were shipbuilders, colliery owners, they thought they were upper class but sometimes they w
ere rather lower class. It was money class with them. And then there was the Lamptons and the Ravensworths, they were the Upper Ten, the real aristocracy which kept themselves to themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And what about other people like yourself, that you say belonged to the lower middle class, who would they have been? What sorts of people?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, there was clergymen and doctors, professional people, really. Wouldn't you say so?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And what about the people who were very poor, the miners, and what other sorts of people would you say were the poorest class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Lower class? Well, some worked on the railway and some worked ... what we called 'down the water', that was in the shipyard, labourers, and ... but they were very honest and very good people many of them. They were really good living, decent people.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. My father would not allow it. He wouldn't beck and bow to anybody. Mother wa
s inclined to rather ... like, a minister coming, or a solicitor or a doctor, but it made no difference to Father, he didn't care who they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And were you brought up to behave the same or differently to different sorts of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, I went
 to a school that was a bit of a ... I always thought it was a bit snobbish, because had to go round the High Road to avoid the Board School children, you see, so we thought we were better but we were not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Would you, for instance, be expected to behav
e differently to, say, the doctor than you would to, say, somebody who worked down on the water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, it all depended on the character of the man. My father respected a good character more than a profession and of course, I might have got that from 
him, I don't know. I never regarded anybody, really, better or worse. I used to collect Father's rents every ... we had some houses, and there were a few - pitmen lived in them, and he wouldn't collect the rent, Mother wouldn't collect the rent, so I coll
e
cted the rent from being very small, but I loved to go to the poorer houses because they kept whippets, Yorkshire terriers and pigeons, and they generally had puppies and things which I liked, and they generally offered you food, what they were making, an
d they were kindly, really nice people and I liked them. I like that class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were you ever told to curtsey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, no! Father ... and Miss Elliott, no, she would not stand up when they played The King!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 That's your schoolteacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes. She used to say 'yes, stand up when Beethoven playes, or Mozart, but not The King!'
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 So you never had to curtsey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never!!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have to ever show respect in a particular way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, you never had to be rude to anybody, but you weren't brou
ght up to think that anybody was better than you. We never thought anything about it. But Father never ... he was himself and he wouldn't try to ... he'd give respect where respect was due but he wouldn't ... Well, you know the sort. Now, there was a man 
w
orked on the road, we called him Willie Dunn and he lived alone in a cottage with a spaniel dog, and he had a gun and he used to shoot. And once Father said to Mother 'now, I'm bringing a real gentleman in to tea to-day', so poor Mother got everything nic
e and it was Willie Dunn. But he was a real gentleman. A gentle, old fellow, he was, and good. But he wasn't the Upper Ten, he was just the road man, he swept the roads.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever call anyone 'sir', or 'master' or 'madam'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents? In these ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes. Yes, all my father's tenants had great respect for my father, and a lot of the poor people had because they never asked in vain if they were a deserving case.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And would they call him 'sir'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, or maybe 'governor', or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember them doing things like touching their cap, or the women curtseying or anything like that to your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. Oh, no, no, no. Never. I never remember anybody curtseying to anybody where I lived.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 It's a much more straightforward community, wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Very straightforward. Oh, no, there was no curtseying or ... Well, we didn't. I don't know if the King or the Pope had come up would have made any difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 In the village who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, anybody that was very rich, because they gave, and I think it was more a matter of wealth. If you were considered a bit above the average it was more wealth than anything els
e. It wasn't really a distinction, but if anybody was wealthy, and there were many wealthy people about there, then they were considered a little bit more, maybe. I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10945156\charrsid2560445 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  our house it wouldn't have mattered had you been a prince or a pawper, you'd have been welcome.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you come into contact with any of these very rich people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes. I had friends among them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I remember you telling me that you had one friend that you used to go away and stay with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Ena? I just had a letter from her yesterday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 She was a daughter of a rich family, was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes, they made money. They had a factory and they made delicacies for the table. And they had beautiful parties and they were very much sought after. But Ena and I, we met ... I was 5 and Ena was
 4 and we've been friends all these years. She must be 71 and I'm 72, now. The letter's there. And she's hard up now and she was just saying she doesn't like to lead this restricted life. She's restricted because she hasn't money to fling away. Her father
 left her plenty of money but her husband was extravagant, she was extravagant and and it came to an end.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And what about shopkeepers in general, people who kept shops? Who did they mix with in general, would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, I think the tradesmen mixed with each other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about clergymen, who would they mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
I rather thank that clergymen liked to be where there was a little bit of money, I don't know. Or where the best table was laid. I may be a bit naughty saying that, but I thin
k so, because they weren't very well paid and had to keep a show and I think if you gave a clergyman a very good lunch or a very good tea you found him often on your doorstep.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about teachers, who did they mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, as a matter of fact
 they mixed with anybody, but there wasn't a lot of time in those days to mix. I suppose they mixed with each other. We had teachers coming to the house, but now many. I think they sort of kept to their own lectures, and what have you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about the farmers? Who would they associate with, do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Farmers were one on their own, you know. They met at the market, came home from the market, and then during the week they were working, perhaps, as long as it was daylight, so they hadn't much time to mix with anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
And what about employers in general? That's any people who were in a situation of employing a number of other people? Who would they tend to mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We employed quite a few people and they never left unless they died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And would your family mix socially with the people that you employed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We didn't, but they used to come to our house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about people who owned factories, or mills and things like that, who would they mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, it really depended
 on the person, because some mill owners may have been of a wild sort of nature and they'd mix with men-about-town. Or maybe another man might have a factory and he was a very good man and he went off to the side of the Church and that's where they got th
e ... Some liked town life and others liked Church, the same as today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What sort of people would you say went to the Church, and what sort to the Chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, there were some good ones, and I think there were quite a number of hypocrites. I didn
't think they were in those days, but since I've grown older and I've looked back I've thought there were maybe a few of them very hypocritical. They were on the whole a very good lot. Father used to think it was expensive to mix with the Devil, but it wa
s just as expensive to mix with the Church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
And what would you say the differences were between the sort of people who went to the Church and the sort of people who went to the Chapel? I mean the differences between the two sorts of people; would you say there were any differences?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, to use a cheap term, the Church people were snootier. They were snooty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And the Chapel people weren't?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. Unless they got on a bit, and then they became just as snooty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When they got on a bit would they still go to the Chapel, or would they go to the Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, but they became the ... you know, the highlights.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Where you lived did all the people in the lower class have the same standard of living? Or would you say there were different 
groups among them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, there were some had a ... maybe a better layout than others, kept a better table and maybe had a house in the country or by the sea, and others didn't. And there were some who kept themselves to themselves, and there's others that spread out a bit.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
In India and these places there was a red rope to divide the classes. He said there was red ropes in chapels and churches but they were invisible, but they were there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Can you describe two sorts of families? You say in the 
lower classes that some people would be slightly better off and keep a better table than another, can you remember a particular family who was like that compared with another one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, it was more extravagance than anything else, and they generally 
went bankrupt, these lot that kept entertaining and this, that and the other, they generally came a flop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And they'd be in the lower classes, would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you think that one group felt itself superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Decidedly! It's always been and always will be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were some families thought of as 'rough' and others as 'respectable'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, yes, yes. There was the respectable class, and there was the rough class, and as far as I can remember when I was young and beginning to
 understand things I always thought the rough class were more genuine than the people who thought they were not rough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Why were they considered rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, they hadn't very good manners, for one thing and ... I don't know they were just rough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember a distinction of this kind being made between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes, there was always a ... A craftsman could always hold his own where a labourer couldn't. He might be noisy and talk a lot, but he hadn't that class about him. A craftsman always had that class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes or groups?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I think my mother, as I've said before, she liked the doctors and the clergymen and the solicitors and all of th
is rubbish, but Father didn't worry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Your father was the same to everyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Same to everyone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I'm positive she did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 She thought we were really very nice, indeed! (laughter) She did. She thought we were lovely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you think that this was because of her parents, or because of your father's.?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I blame it entirely on her Scottish blood and bringing up in Scotland.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I do, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, often a person out of the lower classes }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  a fellow that was better off and they improved and the children improved, naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Would it be possibl
e, for instance, for a man who was poor ... a poor working man, would it be possible that he could ever move to another class? By his own efforts, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, I think it was difficult, especially if he lived in the same village all his life. He may h
ave sort of aped somebody else if he'd gone into another district, but not in the village, he was always what he was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Can you remember anyone who did move to a different class, through marriage or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, I think they mostly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  into the class they'd be mixing with, you see. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Can you remember anyone being described as 'a real gentleman' or 'a real lady'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I've often heard it said, but I paid little attention to what he was or who he was at that time. I was too yo
ung to know whether he was a real gentleman or a real blackguard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Why do you think people said that about them, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Because there were some people who were naturally like that, I think, they can't help it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 The man who worked on the road you just told me about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And he'd be described as a real gentleman?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 He was a real gentleman. My father thought so. And yet there were some real gentlemen who were blackguards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember seeing a policeman round where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes. Oh, yes, there was policemen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Nothing. We thought they were a bad lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, then nobody ... they had no ... from the very lower classes. Then, I'm not saying ... I'm tal
king of a long, long time ago, they had to be picked from people who were brawny and strong, not for any education or anything. As long as you could knock a man down. There used to be awful fights on a Saturday night when people got their pay, because the
 shops were open 'till 12 o'clock and they used to turn the pubs out and then there would be fights. But it was no earthly use getting the copper, you used to send for the Catholic priest and he settled them, brought his stick with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 It was no use getting the copper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No!! The priest, and they fled. They were more terrified of the priest than the copper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you ever remember your mother or father saying 'if you're naughty I'll call a policeman'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, no, they never scared you with dragons or policemen or dogs, or anything. We grew up without a word of a nervous disposition.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How do you think the policemen treated the people in general?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, I think they treated poachers and things like that rather roughly. But on the whole th
ere wasn't a lot of crime. There were crimes, but when crime was committed it was a bad one, it was murder most probably. But no, I don't think there was many bad cases where we were. There were some murders.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 The next question is: was your home rented? I seem to remember that you ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, never. Never. We never had a rented home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember feeling that your parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What difference would it make to the family if your father was, say, ill? He wasn't ever out of work, your father, was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But what if he was ill, what difference would that make?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I don't know because he was never ill. He once had the 'flu. Oh, he was never ... he was always ... Well, it was his own 
business and he had to be there, you see, they couldn't get on without him, or so he thought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When there was someone in the district whom the people disapproved of very strongly, was there any special way in which they showed it?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. Might gossip about them, but that would be all. They didn't show it in any other way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You don't remember anyone making rough music to get them to move out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Or things like effigies being made or bad people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You said that if somebody committed suicide they were buried at the crossroads.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I think they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 That was the story, anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, that was the story. But whether it was to threaten us in case we would ever commit suicide I never knew. But you weren
't allowed in consecrated ground.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you said that prisoners were buried in lime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
If they were murderers. I think if you died in prison for a smaller thing they would bring you out. But if you were a murderer and in for life and died, or were h
anged, well, you were put in the shadow of the prison. Have you ever heard the Ballad of Reading Jail?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 It horrified me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Now we go on to your school. Were you given lessons by one of your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, Father taught me the clock.
 I knew the clock when I was 4, and then he sold that clock with nice little figures and bought a Roman one - this one - and I had to learn all the Roman figures over again. But I knew the clock when I was 4, and I knew a lot before I went to school.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever have a tutor or a governess or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, no, no. Oh, dear no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 When you first started what time in the morning did you go and when did you come back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Half past nine - it was a little private school, an old lady, Miss Stephens, kept it and she was a very good teachers but she was very old. She never opened the windows, or anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you went at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname metricconverter}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname ProductID}{\xmlattrvalue 9.30 in}}}9.30 in
{\*\xmlclose} the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, and we were finish
ed, I think, about half past 12 so we would mix those rotten Council children, and then we went back for, maybe, 2 hours in the afternoon. And she taught us to sew, she was a very good sewer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she teach you anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Nothing much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you went back home at lunchtime, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How long did you have at lunchtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
I think we had, maybe, from half past 12 'till 2 o'clock. You see, it wasn't run by the council and we could do what we liked. It wasn't very ... there was no laws then, you could do what you liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How did you get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Walked. I could see the house from our gate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How long did it take, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, about 3 minutes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Who went with you? Anybody, or did you go by yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I had a boy friend, Phil Wake and he often used to call and carry me slippers. He was so nice, we got on terribly well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did he come home with you as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Where did you have your midday meal, at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 At home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What did you have to eat, then, when you were 4 or 5, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, just an ordinary dinner, the same as Mother and Father and whoever was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, I just used to sit and try to take it in, that was all. We ha
d another mistress and we called her Miss Lizzie, she used to sit on a chair and take a little class, and Miss Stephens was an old woman and had a big desk and she had a big tin of yellow sweets, you know, I forget what they called them, and if you answer
ed well and did well you got one, which was a great pleasure. We thought more of that one sweet we got than a packet that we got from anybody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you like school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How did you feel about the teachers in general, Miss Stephens and Miss Lizzie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, I suppose ... Miss Stephens was very old, to me. So did Miss Lizzie, but Miss Lizzie wasn't old. And I don't think they were well off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you like them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, yes, I liked them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did they emphasise certain things as important in life, like manners and tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, but we weren't a bad mannered lot, really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What about punctuality, would they ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, we were always there on time. And then we had a ... they had a front room and twice a week we 
used to go down into this room and have musical drill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Doing physical jerks and things, with music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did they emphasise ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 If you did something they disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We got the ca
ne, and she called it 'Miss Sweet-lips', and it hung on the end of the mantel shelf, but it was very, very rarely ... I never got the cane. I don't think I ever saw anybody get the cane, but it was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 To remind you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 A menace, and it was Miss Sweet-lips.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did the other children in the school come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Very similar. Often professional parents, or well-to-do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No,
 never, it wasn't thought of in those days. You all got the same. We got to know where America was, and Africa was and where this, that and the other was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were there any gangs or groups in this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Nothing like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were there any children who were left out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You don't remember that, either?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No. They were rather like a very big family, very agreeable and we played together in her garden. Then we came home: you singled some out; some of them used to
 go to little children's parties and, you know, Christmas time, to these little parties, and enjoyed ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you go on to another school after that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Then I went to Miss Elliott's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How old were you when you went to Miss Elliott's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I should think I'd be about 10.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And that was a private school, too, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, but she was a very, very ... well, you saw, a very able woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Was there just herself there, or anybody else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, no. There was Miss Ellen, her siste
r, and there was Miss Greener, and there was a Miss Brown, taught art, she came once a week; and Miss Gertrude Ransome came and taught elocution once a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How did you get to that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Walked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And how far away was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, I should think it would take you maybe 10 minutes, because sometimes we used to dally on the road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What time did you have to be at that school, Miss Elliott's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We used to be at that school at a quarter to nine to 1 o'clock, which was a long morning, but we had no afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No afternoon school. So you went home to lunch, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Hm, to do homework. We had homework to do in the afternoon, but we didn't go back to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Was it a lot of homework?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Quite a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember how long it took you? It didn't take you long. And what did you think of this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, it was nice, I liked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What did you feel about the teachers there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Miss Elliott was a lovely woman, to look at, and character. She was really good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you like her better than the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Well, I never was in anybody else's class but Miss Elliott's, because I went when it was a small school and it grew. Well the other teachers were teaching the younger ones when I was practically 16 or 17, you see. It was a pleasant life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
And did Miss Elliott emphasise certain things as important in life? Did she emphasise the importance of, say, manners and tidiness? punctuality? Ways of speaking, did she ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Can you remember any particular attitudes that she gave you to life? When I say 'attitudes', I mean something special that she gave you.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 All her attitudes. When she taught Shakespeare she lived that character; or Maid of Ancient Rome, or Scott, she lived ... she was one
 of them, which you always remembered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And inspired you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I think it did. And what I learnt at that school I passed on to Dorothy, which she used to like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 If you did something that the teachers disapproved of in this school, say Miss Elliott, what would happen to you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I don't remember anybody doing anything dreadful. I don't remember anybody really getting into trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were there just girls at this school, or boys and girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 There were mostly girls after a certain age. 
You see, the boys left and went to boarding schools, and one thing and another, and there were more girls left than boys. They'd gone away to better ... well, not better schools, but boys' schools, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your parents show an interest in your school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes, but I think they could have shown more, because Father was of an easy disposition and if you wanted to do anything he didn't worry you to do home work or anything. He was indifferent to it. Really, it wasn't the retrace then that it i
s now, it didn't matter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did they ever visit the school? Either the first school you went to, or Miss Elliott's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, the Elliott's and our family were very friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did she come to your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, but she used to go to my father's people often, they were very great friends and we saw them there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember your mother or father asking you what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, I think they just thought we went there to learn our lessons and that was it. Never bothered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And at Miss Elliott's school did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes, yes, very similar. They were all ... well, they had a certain amount of money and good incomes that they could keep you there. They were all people of rather sound ... financially.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And do you remember in this school any children singled out for special treatment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. We had two girls ... were rather retarded. The one hadn't a roof to her mouth and she wasn't clever; and there was another dunce, 
she wasn't very clever although her sister was brilliant, but they weren't singled out, we just knew they were a bit dull and that was that, and you couldn't do much about it. They didn't get special treatment or special tuition, or anything like that.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Were there any gangs in this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, never. Never gangs. We used to go home, if we lived in a certain, you know, district or street, we used to go home together all the girls that lived in that direction we went together, and some that lived i
n another direction, they went the other way. They all went home together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How old were you when you left Miss Elliott's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I left in 1914. I must have been 17, but I didn't stay on for what I learnt or what I was taught, but it was more for compa
ny because I had nobody at home and I think that this left ... Ena stayed on and I stayed on. It was more for company than anything else because we weren't trained for anything and I never worked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Would you have stayed on longer if you could have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
No, I think we were glad.... The War broke out and I think we were glad, we wanted to be, you know, in the swim. I don't know what 'swim' it was, but we thought, you know ....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you have any regrets at all about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, I wi
sh I'd paid more attention and gone further than I did, but nobody pushed you, you see. You knew you hadn't to go out to work which I didn't do, but I suppose nowadays I'd have had to stick harder and get a career.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you think you benefited from your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I'm sure I did. I don't know. I hope I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 While you were at school did you have a little part time job or any means of earning a little regular money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I never earned a penny in my life! 'Till I went to the factory in the last War, and I was never happier.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And that's the first job you had, when you went to the factory in World War II?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes. And when I ... well, I was getting on to 50, then, and when they brought my pay in little squares, I thought they were bringing b
iscuits round for the lunch! (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And that was the first ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 That was the first packet I had, and I just thought then what I'd missed all my life by not having a pay packet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Would you have liked to have worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 I would have liked to have had work and been with other people and had a pay packet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 This is about your home life after you left school: you went on living at home, didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Now, you didn't start full time work at all, but did the fact that you'd left school change your relationship with your parents at all?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Not at all. I had more time to go about with Father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did it change your attitude towards your brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, because he joined up and had to go ... he went to France, you see. I didn't see much of him then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 But you spent more time with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, not with Mother. With Father. I spent more time with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What would you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We went to sale rooms and we went to horse shows and dog shows and agricultural shows, one thing and another like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you spend your Sunday any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No. Of course, when the War came along there was more restrictions and things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Do you remember how that changed things at all? The War?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Well, for one th
ing the schools filled with soldiers and we got to know what Reveille was, and what the Last Post was. And when my brother joined up I didn't know what a Private ment, a private soldier, 'cos he was a Private and I thought he'd been promoted. I thought he
'd got a title. (laughter) 'Cos we weren't an army family at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Never. We were always Tory, and that was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Now you told me how you used to spend your spare time when you were a child, did that change at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Just buggered about! (whispered)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you go on playing games as you'd done when you were a child, or did that stop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, did more reading and this girl, you know, that I mentioned before, her home was still intact. We used to go 
there and they used to entertain soldiers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 That was Ena, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Oh, yes, we used to like that. They were a very musical family and her father bought her a beautiful grand piano and they asked me, if there's an
y poor looking soldier going down, ask him to come to Baden House 'cos they used to entertain soldiers, the poor ones you know that hadn't anywhere to go. So I said 'there's a very poor one', oh, dear, he was a wretched looking creature, so I said, 'would
 
you like to go to ...', you know, Father and I used to stand at the gate and I said 'have you anywhere to go?' and he said 'no'. Well, I said, 'there's a house, an open house and I'm sure you'd like it', and he went. And when he saw the great grand piano 
h
e nearly passed out. He was only the Director of Music of Westminster College. Mr. Thompson said 'you find a few more like that', he said. And Mr. Thompson was instrumental, if that is the right word, in getting him off the Army. He said 'fancy a man with
 
talent like that ...' But they conned them from all parts, you know, in that first World War, they just were dying like flies. It was a much worse war than the second one, you know, it was death at its worst. They just mowed them down and they just had to
 keep filling them up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you go out in the evening after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And what would you do? Who would you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Ena.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And where would you go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Sometimes we went to the Carl Rose and sometimes we went ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 What was the Carl Rosa?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
The opera company. And sometimes we went to the Doyle Carte, and if there was a ... And one time we went to an awful thing, we thought we were really wicked, we went to see Damaged Goods, and we thought we were the last thing! And there was nothing to it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you ever go to dances or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
Yes, private ones. Some of the girls from school had left and they had a party and that, and we would go to a dance, sometimes in their own home sometimes in a hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you make any new friends, boys or girls, at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Not many.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Can you remember any of the ones that you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, they were mostly people that we'd known all our lives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 And you had one special friend, Ena, was she your only special friend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, I had quite a few good friends, but Ena and I always seemed to be together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have any special boyfriend at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Yes, one or two. One that wrote me a nice letter saying next to his sister he loved me best. I wasn't first on the list, Pru was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Who was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 We called him Lofthouse, The Pest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did your parents meet your friends? They presumably did because you'd known them all your life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Oh, I never went out with a strange person in my life!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You'd always bring them home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They'd always just come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did they expect to know where you were when you were out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They always knew where we were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 You'd just tell them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 They knew where we were going and that was that
. And most probably Father or Gordon, my brother, came down to meet me to bring me home because during the War it was a blackout, and it was a bit dodgy so either Father came down or Gordon, if he was at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Did you have to be home by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 No, but we were generally ... you know, about 10-ish, that was the limit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 That was when you'd be back? Now, what age were you when you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 , Mrs. Skinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Good Heavens. I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
 in 1920, so I must have been 23.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How old was your husband when you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 Four years older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4094140 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 How long had you known your husband when you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6834981 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445  him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6712336 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 About 2 years, he was a brother of a friend of mine.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \fi-461\li461\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid4094140 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8744021\charrsid2560445 
\par }}